Convergence: It uses "Expectation-Maximization." First, it assigns points (Expectation), then it updates the center (Maximization).

Weakness: It assumes clusters are spherical and of similar size. It struggles with "Moon-shaped" or elongated data.

2. Hierarchical: Agglomerative Linkage
The "Dendrogram" is built based on Linkage criteria:

Single Linkage: Distance between the closest points of two clusters (can cause "chaining").

Complete Linkage: Distance between the farthest points (creates compact clusters).

Ward’s Method: Minimizes the variance within clusters (usually the most robust).

3. DBSCAN: Density & Noise
DBSCAN requires two parameters: Epsilon (radius) and MinPts (minimum points to form a dense region).

Why it's superior for real-world data: It doesn't force every point into a cluster. If a point is in a "low-density" area, it is labeled as -1 (Noise).

The Logic: It starts with a random point; if there are enough neighbors within Epsilon, a cluster is born. It then recursively adds all "density-reachable" points.

